Data that are not normally distributed. Specifically have non normal but still independent errors. The process of generalized linear model allows use of function F to fit the data on a linearized scale F(y) = F(f(x)) while calculating the variance on an untrasnformed scale in order to correct the distortion that linearization may induce (Bolker 2008)

In GLM ‘F’ is the link function

Link 1. Logit: When f is the logistic curve; F is the logit function; y = f(x); F(y) = log(y/(1-y)) =x, y = (exp(x)/1+exp(x)) Link 2. Log: y = exp(x) Link 3: Square root, y = x^2 Link 4: Inverse, y= 1/x Link 5: Probit, inverse of cumulative distribution function

In GLM, family of non-normal error (exponential) can be handled. It includes: 1. poisson- pick log link function 2. binomial- pick logit link function or log link or probit 3. gamma- inverse or log 4. normal- identity (linear regression)

Fitting glm models

We will use glm of family binomial, with link function logit which assumes both 0 and 1 are equally distributed approximately In linear models, we estimate the parameters by minimizing the sum of the squared residuals. Equivalent to finding parameters that maximize the likelihood.

In a GLM we also fit parameters by maximizing the likelihood. The deviance is -2* maximum log likelihood + c. Estimation is equivalent to finding parameter values that minimize the deviance.

m1<- glm(diabetes ~ age + pregnant, family = binomial(link="logit"), data= pim)

#m2<- glm(diabetes ~ age + pregnant, family = binomial(link="probit"), data= pim)
m2<- glm(diabetes ~ age * pregnant, family = 'binomial', data= pim)
m3<- glm(diabetes ~  age , family = 'binomial', data= pim)
m4<-glm(diabetes ~ pedigree, family = 'binomial', data= pim)

Model selection

m2 is the best supported model

Intercept: related to predictions when the predictor has value 0.

Slope: determines how steeply the probability of diabetes moves from 0 to 1, as age and pregnancy and age*preganncy increases.

Check variance inflation

If you are in doubt about a variable to be included based on p value, you can check values of VIF to see is they should be included VIF >10 suggests models have multicollinarity problem, its gives VIF for each variable.

If the model is correct and when sample size is large, the residual deviance D has a chi-square distribution approximately: residual D ∼ χ2dfResid

# is the chi sq distrbution of deviance correct

Likelihood ratio test

The deviance always goes down as more predictors are added to the model For a series of nested models you can do LRT, anova

m2<- glm(formula = diabetes ~ age, family = "binomial", data = pim)
m1.2<- glm(formula = diabetes ~ age +pregnant, family = "binomial", data = pim)
m1.4<- glm(formula = diabetes ~ age +pregnant+pedigree, family = "binomial", data = pim)
#m1.2 has lower deviance

anova(m2,m1.2, m1.4,test="Chisq")
summary(m1.2)
